  "prompt": "If space (the universe) is a sphere or saddle shape, then what is outside of that? What do you call the empty space outside that comes after?",
  "response": "The concept of \"outside\" the universe is a challenging one because it delves into the philosophical and physical boundaries of our current understanding of cosmology. In standard cosmological models, particularly those based on general relativity, the universe encompasses all of space and time, meaning that there isn't a defined \"outside\" as it exists in a context of its own.\n\nIf we envision the universe as a finite but unbounded shape, like a sphere (where traveling far enough in one direction returns you to your starting point) or a saddle shape (which represents a hyperbolic geometry), then it behaves as a closed system. In such models, there is no \"outside\" space; rather, the geometry of the universe wraps around itself.\n\nThe term used to describe the hypothetical \"outside\" of the universe varies. Some might refer to it simply as \"beyond the universe\" or \"extraverse,\" but these are not scientifically defined terms. In speculative theories, there may be concepts like the \"multiverse,\" which suggests the existence of multiple, perhaps infinite, universes, each with its own distinct properties and dimensions. In this view, \"outside\" could refer to other universes rather than physical space.\n\nUltimately, our understanding of what lies outside the universe, if anything, is still a matter of speculation and philosophical debate, as current science cannot definitively address the question.",
